
AppConfig → used to configure Spring Security
SecurityFilterChain → defines security rules for HTTP requests
HttpSecurity → used to customize authentication & authorization


SecurityFilterChain securityFilterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception{

}

SecurityFilterChain decides which requests are allowed and which are blocked
HttpSecurity = security rules ka builder

Is method ke andar hum batate hain
➡️ Login chahiye ya nahi
➡️ CSRF on/off
➡️ JWT / form login
➡️ Customer vs Restaurant Owner access


http.sessionManagement(
    management -> management.sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS)
)

➡️ Server session save nahi karega
➡️ Har request me token aayega (JWT based auth)
➡️ REST APIs ke liye best practice

.authorizeHttpRequests(Authorize -> Authorize

#AUTHORIZATION RULES
➡️ Yahan hum URL access rules likhte hain

.requestMatchers("/api/admin/**").hasAnyRole("RESTAURANT_OWNER","ADMIN")

#ADMIN ROUTES
➡️ /api/admin/... URLs
➡️ Sirf ADMIN ya RESTAURANT_OWNER access kar sakta hai

.requestMatchers("/api/**").authenticated()

#API ROUTES
➡️ /api/... ke sab endpoints
➡️ Login + valid token required

.anyRequest().permitAll()

#PUBLIC ROUTES
➡️ Baaki sab URLs
➡️ Public access (login not needed)

.addFilterBefore(new JwtTokenValidator(), BasicAuthenticationFilter.class)

➡️ Apna custom JWT filter add kar rahe ho
➡️ Ye filter:
Token check karega
User authenticate karega
➡️ BasicAuthenticationFilter se pehle chalega

